<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Knowing that a large part of this tale is focused and set in the temple of Ana, I can't say I feel fully on-board. I don't like 1052, and depictions of eating disorders is a very hit-or-miss thing for me. Suffice it to say, that angle is a miss for me, both in 1052 and in here. At most, I can chalk that up to it being portrayed as a religious and spiritual kind of thing, in a more abstract way than I'm used to seeing. There's probably parallels to how it's perceived in reality, but it feels more distant here than I'd personally like.</p>
