		<div class="post" id="post-2355304">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2355304)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2355304">
																		Re: Ooook, so proofreading stuff.
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rademacher" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2215205); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2215205&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203958" alt="Rademacher" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2215205)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rademacher" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2215205); return false;" >Rademacher</a></span> <span class="odate time_1439236233 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">10 Aug 2015 19:50</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2355304">
									

<p>In response to <span class="printuser"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/vaelynx" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(914331); return false;">VAElynx</a></span>:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>I have a feeling you (Rademacher) are reading way too much into the piece - not everything has political undertones, and sometimes a hammer and sickle are just tools in a shed rather than a symbol of workers' struggle.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The world's certainly overrun with social alarmism/sensationalism and I'm not here to contribute to that trend. Unfortunately, the hammer and sickle analogy has a crucial flaw that I hope will stand to clarify the intentions behind my critique here.</p>
<p>The hammer and sickle was a symbol used by revolutionaries in Russia to symbolize a political ideology. Its constituent parts, a literal hammer and sickle, are mundane objects. They existed before they were used as a symbol and currently exist with a practical function outside of political association.</p>
<p>Anorexia nervosa is a serious eating disorder and mental health condition that affects an estimated 30 million living people who actively face the social and institutional prejudices associated with mental health conditions. It has no other practical or symbolic function other than as a diagnosis.</p>
<p>When someone includes a living group of people in any piece of media (fiction, visual art, a news report—&nbsp;anything really), they are creating a representation of that group of people. If it's a marginalized group of people, such as people with a mental health condition, then it's necessary to ask whether or not that representation is a respectful, accurate one.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
In response to <span class="printuser"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/djoric" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(388108); return false;">Djoric</a></span>:
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>That, and the Ana cult does not stand out all that much considering that the Daevites also worship Moloch (whose practices require the sacrifice of children) the Mother (an Oedipal sex cult), Able (MURDER EVERYTHING, KILL EVERYONE, WAAAAAAAAAGGGGHHHHH), the Factory (slave away until you die. Then work some more), the Hanged King (horrible acts of cruelty for the entertainment of a distant and ancient monarch), the Flesh (basically the Flood), and have an empire-wide, state-sponsored, all-present dystheist worship of the Scarlet King. (ie God is evil and will fuck you up so keep those sacrifices going and keep that blood flowing and keep his attention ANYWHERE BUT HERE)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Nothing in this passage is relevant to the discussion at hand. We're talking about your piece and how it represents a group of real, living people. Citing the barbarousness of a list of cults is not an effective diversion from that point, nor does it in any way change a single word of your story for the better.</p>
<p>You're also talking about groups that do wanton, morally repulsive things here and comparing them to a metaphor for anorexia. That's entirely inappropriate and demeaning on top of being absolutely ridiculous.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I'd really like to know what I was allegorizing and how, because that was entirely literal. It's a gnostic anorexia cult that takes admonition of the flesh to the extreme end.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&quot;Allegory&quot; refers to an extended, pervasive metaphor, like the metaphor of the fictional temple/cult of Ana as for the eating disorder anorexia nervosa. The cup I'm drinking from right now is part of the real world, so it can't be analyzed as a literary symbol. The temple in your story is a solid object, but it's a fictional, non-literal solid object and those have symbolic qualities.</p>
<p>Gnosticism and an eating disorder are not the same thing and can't be conflated. The restriction and ascetic qualities present in Gnosticism have moral roots; they're intentional, elective, and come from a rejection of physical attachment and overindulgence. The restriction in anorexia nervosa is the result of a pathological fear and body dysmorphia that comes (typically) from a feeling of low self-worth. There can be no such thing as a &quot;gnostic anorexia cult&quot; because the two concepts are inherently different on a prohibitive level.</p>
<p>That being said, I certainly think it's realistic for a sect of Gnosticism to specifically emphasize overindulgence in food as a vice. That's an idea I would gladly get behind. However, there is a huge difference between starvation/fasting and anorexia. If there weren't, we wouldn't have two different words for them.</p>
<p>Similarly, Gautama Buddha's pursuit of fasting as one part of an extreme form of asceticism is not like anorexia and cannot be used to justify its presence.</p>
<p>You can present a hundred more analogies and they will all be fragile and heavily fallacious like the ones above because every single one is made with the goal of defending your work rather than addressing the core criticism, which involves a damaging misrepresentation through the literary treatment of the subject, not its inclusion.</p>
<p>The substitution of &quot;anorexia&quot; here for an appropriate word like &quot;starvation&quot; or &quot;fasting&quot; serves no identifiable end other than to capitalize on the word's emotional load, which is unarguably exploitation. It doesn't matter who came up with the cult; <em>you</em> made the conscious decision to use it here and you are accountable for that.</p>
<p>This is not a debate I'm particularly interested in continuing because I feel like both the situation and our perspectives on it are clear enough that it's not necessary or ultimately productive to draw it out.</p>
<p>I wholeheartedly respect your undeniable right to disagree with my objections and use them to inform your revisions or lack thereof to whatever extent you feel necessary. I also appreciate you taking the time to address them and being willing to do so with civility. I wish you luck with this and your other endeavors.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
					
